Realization
Technologie Stack
To develop the application, a technology stack is chosen. A technology stack is the combination of frameworks, database, programming languages ​​and tools used for the development of the application.

Frontend
The user interface of the application is developed in Vue. Vue is a JavaScript framework created for developing user interfaces. Within the companycompanyY VueJS is a widely used web framework, so there is knowledge within the company to provide guidance. In addition, it is possible to use Vue to develop progressive web applications (PWA). Just like a website, a progressive web app can support multiple platforms from a codebase. A progressive web app ensures that an application can be installed on different platforms such as Mac OS, Linux, Windows and Android. A progressive web app can be installed on the device just like an app and function offline and integrate with other installed applications.

Backend
To connect the devices to each other, the application uses the WebRTC protocol, which creates the protocol for the device through the session description protocol (SDP). The session description protocol is a description of how the device can be reached. The WebRTC therefore requires a signaling server, a server whose task is to mediate the establishment of a connection. The WebRTC protocol has no requirements regarding the signaling server and how it is implemented. However, it is often chosen to implement RFC 7188, where the WebRTC connection is established by using the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) over web sockets.
The use of web sockets provides a constant bi-directional connection, which ensures that there is the possibility for direct communication. When setting up connections and sharing information, it is important that there is a real-time connection so that the connected users are always informed about the status of connections and available users.
The programming language I chose to implement the signaling server is Go (Go-lang). Go is a statically typed programming language developed by Google. Go is a language developed for creating high-performance backend systems that care about concurrency, scalability and reliability. The programming language is also statically typed, which reduces the chance of runtime errors. In addition, Go compiles to a binary, making it easy to deploy on platforms. The Go runtime provides garbage collection, which is not dependent on virtualization as is the case with Java that uses the JVM Andrawos and Helmich, 2017.

WebRTC
The protocol used to develop the application is Web Real-Time Communication, a protocol developed for establishing secure bi-directional real-time communication. The WebRTC protocol is a protocol that is built on the basis of existing protocols.



WebRTC Signaling
Signaling is the phase of the protocol that involves communicating with whom the communication will take place and how the communication will take place. Signaling is done using an existing protocol: Session Descritpion Protocol (SDP). Within the SDP protocol, among other things,
The IPs and ports that are available are specified.
Which codecs the agent supports.
The values ​​for securing the connection (certificate fingerprint).
Exchanging the SDP is done through “out-of-band” communication, the messages are not exchanged using the WebRTC protocol but using another protocol. Given the fact that the communication is “out-of-band”, the protocol does not specify how this communication should take place. Applications can use existing infrastructure such as REST endpoints or web sockets to exchange SDP messages.

async function CreateRtcOffer(userID: string): Promise<Message | undefined> { if (!conn.value.has(userID)) _setupRtcConn(userID)

const connection  =  conn.value.get(userID)
connection.dc = connection.pc.createDataChannel(userID) connection.dc.binaryType = "arraybuffer"
_setupDatachannelEventListeners(connection)
_setupRtcConnEventListeners(connection)

const offer = await connection.pc.createOffer() await connection.pc.setLocalDescription(offer) return {
from: user.getID(), sdp:offer.sdp, target: userID,
type: RequestTypes.Offer
}
}

Code 1: Create offer

Code snippet 1 shows the steps to create an offer. In the connection, information about the unique connection between the users is stored, see code snippet 2. In the offer that is made, the SDP offer is sent with information about who it comes from and who it is intended for, so that the server knows who it is going to. it needs to be sent. The offer will be sent via a web socket connection to the server.


export type Connection { pc: RTCPeerConnection dc?: RTCDataChannel userID: string
}

Code 2: Connection model


func (v *WebsocketMessageValidator)  ValidateMessageOrigin(msg  *data.Message)  error  { if msg.From == "" {
return nil
}

user, err := v.users.GetUserByID(msg.From) if err != nil {
return err
}

if user.RemoteAddr  !=  msg.Conn.RemoteAddr().(*net.TCPAddr)  {
err  =  msg.Conn.WriteMessage(websocket.CloseMessage,  websocket.FormatCloseMessage(1008, if err != nil {
return err
}

err := msg.Conn.Close() if err != nil {
return err
}
log.Printf("DBG -->>  User  %s  Spoofed  a  message\n",  user.Username)

return errors.New("the message was spoofed")
}

return nil
}

Code 3: Prevent spoofing

The code of 3 shows how spoofing of messages is prevented, the server keeps track of the IP address and port of the connection and if this does not match the web socket connection, the user's connection is disconnected.



func (wh *WebsocketHandler) WsRequestHandler(msg *data.Message, user *data.User) error { switch msg.Type {
case data.Offer,
data.Answer:
err := wh.msg.SendTargeted(msg, user) if err != nil {
return err
}
break
}
}


Code 4: handle message

In the code of 4, part of the code is shown about how the server handles the different types of messages. Based on a switch statement, the server knows the action that needs to be performed. When setting up the web socket connection, this involves forwarding the messages. This is done by the server, the handler calls the message service after which the message is validated and forwarded to the target if the message comes from the right person.

async function HandleRtcOffer(offer: SessionDescriptionMessage): Promise<Message | undefined> {
_setupRtcConn(offer.from)
const connection = conn.value.get(offer.from) offer.type = 'offer'
await connection.pc.setRemoteDescription(offer).catch(console.error) const answer = await connection.pc.createAnswer()
await connection.pc.setLocalDescription(answer) return {
from: user.getUserID(), sdp:answer.sdp, target: offer.from,
type: RequestTypes.Answer
}
}

Code 5: answer offer

The code of 5 shows that an answer is made based on the offering that has been received. The remote description of the RTCpeer connection was set and an answer was created and then saved as a local description. After this, the answer to the offer is sent back to the sender of the offer.


async function HandleRtcAnswer(answer: SessionDescriptionMessage) { const connection = conn.value.get(answer.from)
answer.type =  'answer'
await   connection?.pc.setRemoteDescription(answer)
}

Code 6: process answer

The answer is handled in code 6, the remote description of the peer-to-peer connection can be determined. After this, the first part of the exchange is completed. Both users have knowledge of the other user and can exchange ICE candidates.

connection.pc.onicecandidate = (ice) => { const message: Message = {
candidate: ice.candidate, from: user.getUserID, target: connection.userID,
type: RequestTypes.NewIceCandidate
}
ws.SendMessage(message)
}

Code 7: ice candidate event listeners

In the code of 8, the event listener can see the ICE candidates, as soon as an ICE candidate is created it is transferred to the other user via the websocket connection. After the ICE candidates have been exchanged, the peer-to-peer connection is ready to use.

